                <h2><u>Dilution and Concentration</u></h2>
                <p>There are instances in pharmacy practice when a medication needs to be diluted or concentrated. 
                For example, a prescriber may require a concentrated solution or a concentrated syock solution to be diluted for use in a patient. 
                <i>Dilution</i> is achieved by addition of a diluent to the medication. When diluting a medication, the amount of drug doesnâ€™t change but the concentration changes. 
            <br><br>The simplest way to solve these problems is by using the equation:
                </p>
                <div class="formulae"><p>$$ V^o \times C^o = V^n \times C^n $$</p></div>
                <ul>
                    <li>V<sup>o</sup> : volume at the original concentration</li>
                    <li>C<sup>o</sup>: original concentration</li>
                    <li>V<sup>n</sup>: final volume</li>
                    <li>C<sup>n</sup>: final concentration</li>
                </ul>
